1910, a Chicago steelworker accidentally kills his supervisor. He, his
girlfriend, and his little sister flee to the Texas panhandle, where they
find work harvesting wheat in the fields of a stoic farmer.

A love triangle, a swarm of locusts, a hellish fire, Malick captures it
all with dreamlike authenticity, creating a timeless American idyll that
is also a gritty evocation of turn-of-the-century labor.

